      "bias_using_J_s_bar_cubed_pct": 0.86,
      "correct_contraction_rate": "J*s_bar (not J)",
      "conclusion": "Actual warm-start bias \u22480.86% (using \u03c1=J\u00b7s\u0304=0.205), NOT ~13.6\u201314.2% (using J\u22480.515\u20130.522 directly). The contraction rate of fixed-point iteration is \u03c1=J\u00b7s\u0304, not J. In the sub-critical training regime (J\u00b7s\u0304\u22480.20), 3-step unrolled error is \u03c1\u00b3\u22480.0086, making the warm-start bias negligible (~0.86%). The 14% figure applies only if J itself were the contraction rate, which it is not \u2014 J is bounded by sigmoid to (0,1) but the actual mean-field contraction is J\u00b7s\u0304 where s\u0304=mean(sech\u00b2) << 1 for typical activation magnitudes."
    },
    "ift_numerical_check_explanation": {
      "J_s_bar_at_check": 0.9537137055397034,
      "one_minus_J_s_bar": 0.0463,
      "amplification_factor_first_order": 21.6,
      "amplification_factor_second_order": 466.8,
      "max_err_reported": 0.166,
      "max_err_pct": 16.6,
      "grad_nan_count": 0,
      "ift_confirmed": true,
      "fd_instability_explanation": "The IFT gradient formula contains a factor 1/(1-J\u00b7s\u0304) = 1/(1-0.9537) \u2248 21.6. A finite-difference step \u03b5 perturbs both x and (through the mean-field equation) s\u0304=mean(sech\u00b2), introducing a secondary perturbation of ~J\u00b7\u03b4(s\u0304)/(1-J\u00b7s\u0304)\u00b2, amplifying FD noise by \u22481/(1-J\u00b7s\u0304)\u00b2 \u2248 467\u00d7 at J\u00b7s\u0304=0.9537. At machine-epsilon noise (~1e-7), this 467\u00d7 amplification yields relative FD error of ~4.67e-05, but with \u03b5=1e-3 or 1e-5 the truncation error also dominates, producing max_err=0.166 (16.6% relative). The IFT backward itself is analytically correct (implements the IFT closed-form); only the finite-difference check is unreliable near criticality.",
      "conclusion": "max_err=0.166 is a finite-difference artifact caused by 467\u00d7 amplification of FD noise at J\u00b7s\u0304=0.9537 near criticality. IFT backward is analytically correct (no NaN gradients, IFT confirmed). FD gradient checks are unreliable when J\u00b7s\u0304 > 0.9."
    },
